### Description

I moved the code from `ngOnDestroy` to `onCleanup` function inside an `effect` and now I cannot refactor the test case.

To trigger effect in unit test, we use `Testbed.flushEffects()` but how to trigger the clean up function inside the effect?

Example:

```ts
effect((onCleanup: EffectCleanupRegisterFn) => {
  // ... some code

  onCleanup(() => {
    if (this._scrollbarsRef) {
      this.appRef.detachView(this._scrollbarsRef.hostView);
      this._scrollbarsRef.destroy();
    }
  });
});
```

```ts
 it('should destroy the dynamically created component', () => {
    const hostViewDestroySpy: jasmine.Spy = spyOn(scrollbar._scrollbarsRef.hostView, 'destroy');

    // trigger onCleanup??

    expect(hostViewDestroySpy).toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
```

Previously when code was inside `ngOnDestroy` I could just use

```ts
 it('should destroy the dynamically created component', () => {
    const hostViewDestroySpy: jasmine.Spy = spyOn(component._scrollbarsRef.hostView, 'destroy');

    component.ngOnDestroy();

    expect(hostViewDestroySpy).toHaveBeenCalled();
  });
```

